segments.text: We're in Clemson, South Carolina, sitting on the back porch that's now been glassed in of the home where Dr. and Mrs. Williams lived for a number of years while they were here on the faculty at Clemson.
Mrs. Williams, would you please sum up?
Margaret, would you please summarize for us briefly a sketch of where you all served before coming to College Station?
Well, we had this back porch.
from 1961 until 1966 before we moved to Austin, Texas.
We thank this Commissioner of Higher Education.
Here at Clemson... We lived in this house, but we came in the 40s.
And he came as a faculty member.
As an instructor.
And he left as the academic vice president.
And it had been delightful years of college.
We raised our children here.
And...
lifelong friends.
Well, you won't be testing now, so you don't want to push the recording.
Tom, only two years when he was commissioner, and he worked in all the states and colleges in Texas.
He worked with them all.
Did the best he could with writing a program.
He wrote a program for a plan, and when he finished the plan, he thought it was time to go.
And at that time, he had some other offers, and one of them was
Can you summarize for us how A&M and the Williamses came together?
Who came to visit, and how, and why, as far as you know?
The link with A&M.
The board came to visit with you all.
Oh, yeah.
That was Ford Albritton, Mr. Chairman.
Clyde Wells.
That's the three I remember.
There may have been others.
You'd have to check into that.
How long did they visit?
They came in on Sunday and stayed through Monday as far as I know.
All I can remember is I got them a room at the motel.

uh couldn't you know plan for the country club because it was a monday i remember it was a monday so they had to eat at the hotel i wasn't going to feed them you know i hope you haven't left at all were there any uh were there any previous discussions between texas a m and y'all before that time had uh mr rutter and mr rudder had contacted jack before he died
And since I wasn't privy to hearing that conversation, I know that he had said he would consider it.
And then we got word that he had done it.
And then he got word that these people wanted to come to see him.
And he told me to make the arrangements.
All right.
Y'all came, I believe, November 1, 1970.
He did.
About how long ahead of time did this group come to visit y'all in Knoxville?

I might even find a letter if I went through the file that he had written back saying that he believed in coordination, that the med school and the law school would have to work into a plan like that.
I remember his saying to me that he also asked them to give him their backing to designate a dormitory for women beginning in 1971 so that there would be a place for women to live on campus.
Well, I knew that that happened.
They even put in hair dryers.
But that wasn't the first thing that was requested of him when he got there.
What was the first thing?
Well, the first thing was, we want you to fire the coach.
And his answer was, no, you give them a year's notice.
And the second was a request from the students who wanted

girls in their dormitories, in their rooms, and his answer was, I have two daughters, you all are fine young men, I would like for my daughters to get to know you all, but not in your dormitory where there's no place to sit except on the bed.
And that worked.
Do you want that?
Obviously he didn't.
What similarity was there between Clemson,
where you all had had a long experience, and Texas A&M.
How were the schools similar?
Lynn Grant.
That's as far as I know, and both of them after World War II going co-ed.
Did they have much school spirit?
Yes.
Were there many traditions?
Not like Texas A&M, I don't believe.
I don't believe the traditions here.
This was a period when I was teaching school and raising two daughters, so you can see that I did my beauties with Jack's work, but you know, I wasn't.
It was after World War II when things were growing and the faculty was new.
I imagine they were very much alike, don't you?
Oh, very, very.
Like I tell people, they were both off the main highway
a long distance from the state capitol where the other state university is, and that I assume that Gamecocks tell Clemson jokes the way Longhorns tell Aggie jokes.
All the Aggie jokes go all over the United States because of the Aggie schools.
Sure.
The Morrill, Morrill, is that the name?
Morrill Act.
Act.
And so they all were put out in the country because it was an Aggie school.
Yeah.
Among the key people that I know Dr. Williams worked with was John Calhoun.
Yes, he was a gift from heaven.
He couldn't have been more fortunate to have John Calhoun there.
They had known each other previously.
Jack had looked him up.
Do you remember the speech?
In the speech he told about Jack looking up because of his name.
And then they knew each other when Jack was commissioner.
And he had him that entire time as a loyal, talented...
Turn it off and I'll tell you what I said about him.
Don't say anything you don't want on here.
We'll do that later.
Say only the things you want recorded.
Have you got it on?
Yeah, it's on.
Okay.
John was a brilliant man.
And his wife was lovely and very supportive of him.
And I don't think that Jack could have been more fortunate than to have had John.
And with the two of them, they put an academic team together that compared to none anyplace.
And it wasn't one that they were known for the smallness of their team and how it all worked together.
And I don't remember any conflicts.
I don't either.
I don't either.
I don't remember anybody having any great uproar over anything.
And the same thing happened with his staff in the office.
Nelda Rowell.
Nelda Rowell was, you just can't estimate how much she meant to Jack because she was willing to be an assistant and she knew what assisting somebody meant.
It meant be honest with them and
help them in any way you can.
And she was as loyal as anybody I've ever known.
If she ever saw a letter or an item that she thought might need a little more time or a little more review, what was her technique?
Her technique was saying, Dr. Williams, I don't believe I would mail this today.
What was his route?
Let's make believe it's a typical Monday through Friday, and I know no day was typical.
What was his average routine for the day?
He got up about what time and did what in what sequence?
Well, we had a pattern.
We didn't have any servants in the house for breakfast.
I cooked his breakfast, and I put a card table up in the kitchen under a light because the lighting in the family dining room, he couldn't read the paper by the chandelier.
And so I put a card table up over one of the lights in front of one of the ovens in the kitchen.
And I sat on the stool at the counter and ate my breakfast.
And he sat at the card table and read the paper and ate.
And we had that time together.
And did he sometimes read news items to you from the paper?
No, no.
But we had that meal together.
And if
If he came home for lunch, we put our food on the tray and took it back to the office so it would be private.
What time did he get up and do mail early in the mornings?
He finished up everything at night.
He wouldn't have gone to bed with something that wasn't dictated.
And the office staff told Barry that he'd bring them in all these tapes and they'd type them up and then he'd hand them another set.
But they never got caught up.
But he had a happy staff as far as I can tell.
It ran smoothly, and he didn't have anything unpleasant except one person that he didn't think was loyal.
He didn't put that in there.
Let's see.
Melda, John Calhoun.
Haskell Monroe.
Haskell was the one, if you want to know anything, ask Haskell, because he has lunch every day with a different faculty member.
And he knows everything that's going on.
If you want some information, go to Haskell.
You had a good way, Haskell had a great way of knowing what was going on on the campus.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Dick Winerdi.
Dick is a fascinating man.
He has a lot of energy and enthusiasm and talent.
He was recently, a year or two ago, he was the man of the year for Houston, Texas.
And he is the person who should have the job as president, as far as I'm concerned, right now as president of the Texas Medical Center because of his many talents and his engineering expertise.
When you all got to A&M, do you think Dr. Williams had any specific goals in mind for A&M?
things he wanted to work on?

He had so much experience with the Southern Association that he would have known, he was always a member on the commission of the Southern Association, and he would have known what all the universities needed to be because he'd been doing accreditations for all the universities, so he knew.
Did he dream of a medical school, you think, when you all got there?
Was that...
visiting board members who came to interview him in Knoxville said they would like to have one.
And his answer was, if it can come, as it should, through coordination, if the time can come.
But I do believe in coordination, and we can all have everything we want.
Describe, as far as you recall, how the A&M Press came to be.
Who was it that got Wardlaw and Williams together?
John Lindsay.
Telephone call from John Lindsay.
And he tells one story slightly different from mine because I wasn't in that conversation.
I just know that Jack said that bring him in and that he was interested when John called.
And when he did come to our house, he looked at the coffee table and he says, there's my book.
And I have a book
That was his first success book when he was editor of South Carolina University Press.
And I've heard him tell the story of how they worked him into doing this.
And it doesn't have his name in it.
I had no idea that it was his book.
And he thought I had put it out just for him.
But the first thing he saw, and the name of it, he said he went to bed one night.
He's going to bed, and he didn't have a name for his book.
And he was going to press, and all at once he remembered a line from a poem by the state poet.
Thank him who placed us here beneath so kind a sky.
So he entitled his book Beneath So Kind a Sky.
And it's a picture, historical picture and story of the old historic places in South Carolina.
Let's see.
I know that y'all were close friends of Buck Shewitz.
Well, that was one of the nicest things that's ever happened to me was to know Buck Shewitz because he was one of the most interesting people I've ever known.
You know, he was lovable.
And Texas A&M, of course, he deserved them and they deserved him.
Is that okay to say?
Those two fit together.
They do.
They do.
He was just a delightful character and a talent.
Even with the sad things that happened to him.
Now, he did a drawing or an engraving or whatever the proper artistic term would be of the president's house at College Station.
A Christmas card.
I had requested that he do a scene on the campus of students.
Instead of that, he sat in a car for three days.
Well, I wasn't in town then, and did this picture of the president's home.
And when I saw it, I said, I'd like to buy it.
And he said, you can't afford it.
Then he gave it to me for a Christmas present.
And when I left Texas A&M, I turned it to the university, and it's in their collection.
Let's see, describe the campus as you recall it when you all first arrived.
What were the important structures that were there?
Well, the Rudder Tower was new.
I remember the first evening with Van Claverin for our first opening of the, what was it?
The Rudder Auditorium.
The Rudder Auditorium.
That was, to me, a very exciting evening.
I remember Harold Dunn and Mr.
I'm trying to think of the other name of the building.
Kruger?
Kruger.
When they named that, both were pleased to have their name on that.
I was the MC that night.
I remember that.
Polly and Mr. Dunn, well, that was nice.
And both of them were just delightful people to know.
And I'm glad that...
that I knew so many of the people who had their name on the buildings.
Mr. Pat Zachary, Mr. J. Harold Dunn.
This means a lot to me to have known them and know that they were worthy of being honored in such a way.
Mr. Evans.
Describe Mr. Evans in personality.
Shy.
Hesitant, outgoing, good humor, what?
I didn't know him that well.
Oh, okay.
I just saw him on occasions in the day of that dedication.
He was in, I'm trying to think the name of his plantation.
We got correspondence from him very often.
Little Eva Plantation.
He sold that a little while later.
But I remember that.
been heading on his stationery for that, and then I pushed her wheelchair the day of the dedication.
And that the Friends of the Library organization was an outgrowth of the new library with his name.
Do you know, does your trivia information recall why it was the Little Eva Plantation?
I don't think I ever knew.
That character from Uncle Tom's Cabin,

is buried there little eva and for a while he transferred the title of that to a m and i was the one to try to worry about it and i was worried that some villain was going to get in there and destroy and thank goodness he came a few months later and said if you'll give it back i'll give you land in texas worth a heck of a lot more and so we very gladly made that exchange this man john lindsay you mentioned him
Describe John Lindsay and your feelings about him.
He and his wife are lovely people, of course.
And it was obvious that he was interested in the university.
And I think it's well known that he's responsible for the press.
He had Frank Wardlow at his home.
And he asked him would he be willing to start a press for Texas A&M.
far as I understood he said he would.
And so he called Jack and Jack said bring him in.
That's the words I heard.
Now I heard him make a speech and tell a funny story about their meeting over in Austin.
Tell the funny story.
Well the funny story was that Frank didn't want to be seen with the president of Texas A&M so they picked a small motel someplace that they weren't too happy to be
They're meeting him, but they still, that way, Frank wouldn't be in any trouble for having a meeting and giving somebody the idea that something was going on.
As far...
I know why he wanted to leave.
It was a period, and you don't have to erase this.
It was a period when he was getting transferred to report from different people, wasn't it?
That wasn't the story I heard.
The story I heard, and we had the press right there.
Back to this man Lindsey.
What areas of A&M do you think John Lindsey was interested in?
All of it as far as I'm concerned.
He just was interested in A&M and wanted to help.
And I was close to the press story, but he was just always there with an idea and supporting it in every way.
But there were so many.
Aggies that really love their university and are willing to do anything for them.
But John stands out.
He stands out and he's still there.
He's still there trying to help.
And Sarah was a good, interested person.
She was supportive of him.
And I don't know why he had any greater love or that he had any greater love for this university than a lot of the other performance students.
But he never stopped.
Trying to help.
Buck Wirus.
Well, I just love to hear him.
He's such a good buddy.
And he was good for Jack, and he traveled with Jack.
And once he told me, you can right turn it on.
Tell us about Wirus taking him to a high school to speak to some parents.
Well, Buck told me that he told Jack, he said,
I don't know what you can talk about having a barbecue in a high school gymnasium with people and their children are there.
This is a family affair.
And I don't know what you can talk about.
And he said Jack got up and talked about the lessons of history.
And he said he had complete attention from everybody.
He just never seen anything like him getting up and giving them a history lesson.
When I would hear Dr. Williams make speeches,
I was always deeply impressed with his reference file in his brain of having an appropriate anecdote or story or illustration for that particular event.
Did he have a file that he went through?
Did he have them in a book?
Where did he get all of those recollections?
They were all stored away in his brain.
They were there.
He was, when he died, he had given a book to the President of the Medical Center Board, and on somebody the great, what's his name, the great?
Frederick the Great?
Frederick the Great, I guess it was.
And he came in and he looked, and see where Jack was in his book.
And he said, I've read more than he and Jack haven't finished it.
But I didn't say, Jack's reading three books at a time.
Jack never moved a book.
He had a book where he would sit down or lie down.
And he read the book that was close to it.
And so Peter the Great is the name of it.
Oh, OK. See how it probably takes me to get a name to fly up?
What was Dr. Williams' relaxation?
What did he do to ease off?
He liked music.
Okay.
After his heart attack, even all the old movies would be on.
He read books.
Any particular variety of music?
Well, he liked classical music, and you ought to see his music collection back here.
You ought to see the collection where he's got a tape that he...
He did everything the Reader's Digest at the university ever had and recorded it all.
I even have recordings of him singing with the music and drumming with two pencils, the erasers of two pencils.
He entertained himself by recording himself and singing.
He was a drummer now, a drum major for the high school band, the drum and bugle corps.
I have tapes where he just recorded himself doing that.
He was the Drum and Bugle Corps drum major in Galax?
Uh-huh, for the Drum and Bugle Corps.
And the summer he went to college, before he went to college at 16, he went to Denver, Colorado for six weeks to train their Drum and Bugle Corps.
Now he grew up in Galax?
During that time he was there.
His father changed him from BPI, where he had a football scholarship,
Emory & Henry College and told him when he came through, Emory and Virginia would get off the train and his trunk would be there.
He said, you've already broken your wrist and chipped your tooth and I don't want you playing football.
So he changed him while he was away without consulting him.
Why Emory and Henry?
Do we know why Emory and Henry?
Somebody came to see him and recruited him.
And did he start out with a history major?
No, he was pre-law.
He was going to be a corporate lawyer.
And this is an interesting story.
He played tennis with the older men in town.
He was a lawyer's partner in tennis.
And he wanted to join his law firm, and so he was going to go into corporate law.
And when he came back from World War II, he graduated and joined the Marine Corps December the 8th.
It took them almost two years before they could place him in an altar transfer.
So in the meantime, he started teaching, and they transferred him to a high school where he was a principal.
And he had so many problems with the students up there in the mountain area that at one time he went into town and swore out a warrant for them and had them arrested and taken to the courthouse.
And their parents, they were throwing snowballs with rocks at them.
And he came back from World War II and said, I'm going into education.
Men are needed in high schools.
Men are needed for discipline.
He went to Emory University and started in on education.
And his professor said, you're wasting your time.
If you will come and major in history, we will give you a scholarship.
He didn't apply for it.
And that, people change in your whole life.
But Jack was an avid reader, always.
He was methodical in everything he did.
He kept good records.
He threw everything away.
He didn't clutter his life.
How did he come to be a major in Southern history?
Probably was a professor or something like that.
It was social history.
When Duke University interviewed him, they would have hired him if he had agreed to be a professor.
take a tenure period and be a specialist in that period.
And he said, no, I'm social history.
How did he and Dr. Wiley?
He was one of his professors.
And they were good friends.
They liked each other.
And in one of the classes, he gave his students a copy of Billy Yank or Johnny Redwood.
Johnny Redwood would have been first.
And Jack, I remember him sitting there with that marking.
He didn't know the slang for the military.
This is one of the things that he had bad slang and things like that in it for the men.
And so he corrected him.
And he was the only one in the class that did.
So that was it.
Now, when did you and that young man meet?
He went to college at 16.
I went to college at 18.
I'd been in West Virginia where they had another extra year in junior high.
And he'd been in Virginia where they had one less year.
So he was two years ahead because I'd had an extra year and he'd had one less than the normal folks.
And I was there about, as a freshman,
And that would have been in 38.
I was born in 20.
Is that coming out all right?
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
I've been there about a month.
At?
At what school?
Henry Henry College.
Okay.
My daddy wanted me to go to a girls' school, and I told him I wanted to go to Henry Henry.
And my brother is in the same fraternity, and he asked him to bring some skirts that I had left home to be in rehab.
And he asked me...
where I was, you know, ask somebody to tell him that he'd put them behind a standing mirror.
And when I walked into dinner, we ate at different tables in the dining hall, and I walked in, he said, who is that?
And he told me three or four times before the meal was over where they were.
He started sending me flowers from his table every meal of them.
He'd take a flower out of the vase and send it to me.
And that was my freshman year, the first month or six weeks.
But he broke the first date we had for a football game.
He didn't have the courage to tell me that he was supposed to go to a dance at Virginia Univ.
And he kept saying, well, you go to the first football.
You turned that off, I hope.
No, no, no.
We want this.
This is good.
Oh, my.
No, this is good.
There's nothing bad about this.
I'll show you how smart I was.
You're a freshman, and he's a junior?
And he kept saying, will you go to the first football game with me?
And I said, yeah.
And one day we were walking along, and the date came up, but when is the first football game?
And it was a dead silence.
Well, I already knew that he went to Virginia Intermont Dance, which is a girls' school in Bristol.
And then he had a stag line because he was the only one that knew a certain dance, the shag.
And so the girls lined up to dance with him.
And this dance was the day of the, the next dance was the day of the football game, and of course he already had a date for it.
But he didn't open his mouth.
He didn't tell me he was going to break the date.
He just didn't show up.
But I knew when there was a dead silence that he wasn't going.
So I went up and told all my friends that Jack was going to break a date with me.
This was early in the year, first football game.
So we went to it, and it never was brought up again.
He acted like that evening never existed, and I did too.
It was never mentioned.
He never went to another dance at the Virginia In-N-Out.
He started dating a preacher's daughter who hadn't really learned to dance and no, did really learn.
But what I'm saying is he just kept quiet.
That was a characteristic.
